[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Young is a 73-year-old gentleman who has never in the past sought medical attention.  He presented to the Emergency Department today with the above-stated chief complaint.  Additionally, he has experienced a 30-pound weight-loss in the last four months.  Progressive anorexia.  He has been experiencing nausea but no emesis.
Evaluation in the Emergency Department included an abdominal pelvic CT, and this revealed a 9 x 6-cm regular mass in the sigmoid colon, numerous hepatic lesions.  Bilateral hydronephrosis and ureterectasis down to the bladder with no obstructing stones seen.  Bladder is irregularly thick-walled.  Mr. Young does endorse symptoms of prostatism with frequency and urgency.
Additionally, Mr. Young reports decrease in the caliber of his stools for the last year or so.  He is currently denying abdominal pain.

